      <hedline>
        <hl1>Even More Mired Than Jerusalem</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Charles Hexter letter says there are creative solutions to the Jerusalem conundrum but there is no way to reconcile Israel's demand for the legitimacy of a Jewish state with Palestinian desire to undermine that (July 31 Bernard Avishai Op-Ed)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Mideast Peace Is Ahead of the Talks,'' by Bernard Avishai (Op-Ed, July 31):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Mideast Peace Is Ahead of the Talks,'' by Bernard Avishai (Op-Ed, July 31):</p>
        <p>President Clinton, Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel and Yasir Arafat, the Palestinian leader, all find it politically expedient to lay the blame on differences with regard to Jerusalem, but the actual problem is much deeper and even less amenable to solution.</p>
        <p>There are creative solutions to the Jerusalem conundrum, as Mr. Avishai points out, as well as to the problem of refugees, to the Israeli settlements and to Palestinian and Israeli territorial claims. But there is no way to reconcile Israel's demand for the legitimacy of a Jewish state in the Middle East with the Palestinian desire and action to undermine that.</p>
        <p>CHARLES HEXTER  Rehovot, Israel, July 31, 2000</p>
      </block>
